Part I - (Prosper Loan Data)¶

by (Purity Chepkurui)¶

Introduction¶

Loan Data from Prosper: This data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others. See this data dictionary to understand the dataset's variables.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The ProsperLoan dataset has 113937 entries and 81 columns.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

Loan status is my main feature, i want to know how loan being fully repaid is dependent on the other features.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

  • The variables that will help support my investigation are: Term, Occupation, LoanOriginalAmount, EmploymentStatus, MonthlyLoanPayment, IncomeRange, ProsperScore, BorrowerRate

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

There was no need for any transformations other that changing the data types of some variables. Also, after plotting, it was found that some features should be changed to 'Categorical' like IncomeRange, other features like ProsperScore are almost fixed to specific values, but prefered to keep in numeric format so as to be able to do some calculation on it like average if needed. Majority of borrowers have a prosper count of 4 followed closed by 6 then 8. The least being 1. Majority of the borrowers fall under $(25000-49999) income range. Majority of the borrower rate ranges between 15% and 20% There is a peak between 100 and 200 monthly payments. Majority of the loan status is current, followed by completed and the least is cancelled

It was noticed there are some outliers in the MonthlyLoanPayment and LoanOriginalAmount that are too far away from most of the values, in some charts these outliers are igonred by limiting the axis values.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

Some features such as MonthlyLoanPayment and LoanOriginal Amounthad long-tailed, skewed distributions, these were checked on a log-scale which revealed the hidden distribution in some areas.

#term vs loan status

plt.title('Term vs LoanStatus');
plt.xlabel('Term in months')
plt.ylabel('Count(sum(1))')
plt.show()
  • Loans whose term is 1 year have a higher completed status.
  • Loans whose term is 5 years have a higher current status.
  • The shorter the term of the loan the higher the chances of being completed.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

The lower the term, the higher the monthly loan payments, as seen with 12 months term having the highest monthly loan payments. The longer the term, the higher the loan original amount.

ProsperScore and BorrowerRate have a negative correlation. Borrower rate increases with decrease in ProsperScore. The higher the risk the higher the borrower rate. Majority of the borrowers fall under loan Status (completed, current and charged off). Most of higher prosperscore and lower borrower rate fall under current loan status.

Conclusions¶

Past Due loans generally have higher interest rates in all employment statuses Term, ProsperScore, LoanOriginalAmount, MonthlyLoanPayment, BorrowerRate affect the status of the loan. They determine whether a loan is complete, current, past due, charged-off.
